{
    "level": "A1",
    "intro": "To make a negative with <strong>to be</strong>, put <strong>not</strong> after <strong>am / is / are</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "am not",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "With <strong>I</strong>, use <strong>am not</strong>.",
            "example": "I am not tired."
        },
        {
            "label": "is not / isn't",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "With <strong>he / she / it</strong>, use <strong>is not</strong> or <strong>isn't</strong>.",
            "example": "She isn't busy."
        },
        {
            "label": "are not / aren't",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "With <strong>you / we / they</strong>, use <strong>are not</strong> or <strong>aren't</strong>.",
            "example": "They aren't at home."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Negative forms",
    "intro": "The full form is useful for clear stress; the short form is common in everyday speech.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "I",
            "title": "am not",
            "subtitle": "I am not late."
        },
        {
            "label": "He / She / It",
            "title": "is not / isn't",
            "subtitle": "He is not hungry. / He isn't hungry."
        },
        {
            "label": "You / We / They",
            "title": "are not / aren't",
            "subtitle": "We are not ready. / We aren't ready."
        },
        {
            "label": "Pattern",
            "title": "Subject + be + not",
            "subtitle": "She is not here. / They are not students."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How it works",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Full form",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "The full form is often used when you want to sound clearer or stress the negative more.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She is not at school.",
                    "ua": "She is not at school."
                },
                {
                    "en": "We are not tired.",
                    "ua": "We are not tired."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Short form",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "In everyday speech, <strong>isn't</strong> and <strong>aren't</strong> are more common.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He isn't busy.",
                    "ua": "He isn't busy."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They aren't my friends.",
                    "ua": "They aren't my friends."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Contrast with affirmative",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "Compare the affirmative and the negative to see exactly where <strong>not</strong> goes.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She is ready. → She isn't ready.",
                    "ua": "not comes after is."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They are at home. → They aren't at home.",
                    "ua": "not comes after are."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Affirmative vs negative",
    "intro": "The form of to be stays in the sentence: you only add <strong>not</strong>.",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "I am at home.",
            "ua": "I am not at home.",
            "note": "am + not"
        },
        {
            "en": "She is happy.",
            "ua": "She isn't happy.",
            "note": "isn't = is not"
        },
        {
            "en": "They are students.",
            "ua": "They aren't students.",
            "note": "aren't = are not"
        }
    ],
    "warning": "📌 Do not add <strong>do / does</strong> to negatives with <strong>to be</strong>."
}

{
    "title": "4. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Putting not before the form of to be.",
            "wrong": "❌ She not is tired.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">She is not tired.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Adding do to to be.",
            "wrong": "❌ They don't are ready.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">They aren't ready.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Mixing am not with isn't / aren't.",
            "wrong": "❌ I isn't late.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I am not late.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "5. Short summary",
    "items": [
        "Negative with <strong>to be</strong> = <strong>am / is / are + not</strong>.",
        "With <strong>I</strong>, use <strong>am not</strong>.",
        "With <strong>he / she / it</strong>, use <strong>is not</strong> or <strong>isn't</strong>.",
        "With <strong>you / we / they</strong>, use <strong>are not</strong> or <strong>aren't</strong>.",
        "You do not need <strong>do / does</strong> in negatives with <strong>to be</strong>."
    ]
}

